 in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Missin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Missin","meanings":["English: locative name from Messing (Essex)."]}]},{"name":"Mechtild","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mechtild von Meissen was born in 1120, in Wettin, Saalkreis, Saxony-Anhalt, Germany, her father, Dedo IV von Wettin, was 35 and her mother, Bertha von Groitzsch Margravine of Groitzsch and Wettin, was 25. She married Rapoto II von Abenberg. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. She died on 9 January 1197, in Abenberg, Roth, Bavaria, Germany, at the age of 77."},"et":{"1120–9 January 1197":"1120–9. jaanuar 1197","1120–1197":"1120–1197","1122–1172":"1122–1172","1138–1224":"1138–1224","1163–Male":"1163–Surnud","1167–Male":"1167–Surnud","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1086–1124":"1086–1124","1095–1144":"1095–1144","16 December 1124":"16. detsember 1124","1120":"1120","1197":"1197","1163":"1163","1086":"1086","16 May 1144":"16. mai 1144","1095":"1095","1172":"1172","1170